'''''Congregation''''' is the third [[studio album]] by American [[alternative rock]] band [[The Afghan Whigs]], released January 31, 1992, on [[Sub Pop]]. After touring for two years in support of their 1990 album ''[[Up in It]]'', the band received $15,000 advance from Sub Pop to record a follow-up album. It was primarily recorded at Bear Creek Studios in Woodinville and Buzz's Kitchen in Los Angeles during July to August 1991. The band's frontman [[Greg Dulli]] produced the album entirely with audio engineer Ross Ian Stein. The album's production and release were hindered by Sub Pop's financial difficulties, which were eventually resolved by the massive commercial success of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s 1991 album ''[[Nevermind]]''.

Expanding on the aggressive sound of the band's previous work, ''Congregation'' has more refined musical details and slower songs such as ballads. Its music also incorporates [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[funk]] influences. The album's cover depicts a nude black woman holding a white baby in her arms and alludes to the band's [[African-American music]] roots. The songs have themes of pleasure and guilt, and deal with topics such as dysfunctional relationships and sexual deviancy. Conceived during the burgeoning [[grunge]] scene, the album has been viewed by music writers as stylistically distinct from other Sub Pop and grunge music.

Upon its release, ''Congregation'' was very well received by music critics, who praised its musical quality, stylistic elements, and emotional content. It was promoted with two [[single (music)|singles]], "Turn On the Water" and "Conjure Me", and The Afghan Whigs' extensive touring in the United States and Europe. Although it did not [[record chart|chart]], the album helped the band attain a [[cult following]] and receive offers from major record labels, leading to their signing to [[Elektra Records]]. Since its initial reception, ''Congregation'' has been viewed by writers as the band's breakthrough album and a significant release in [[rock music]] during the 1990s.

== Background ==
After forming in 1986 in Cincinnati, [[The Afghan Whigs]]<U+2014>vocalist and rhythm guitarist [[Greg Dulli]], bassist John Curley, lead guitarist Rick McCollum, and drummer Steve Earle<U+2014>released their 1988 debut album ''[[Big Top Halloween]]'' on an independent record label and gained the attention of Seattle-based label [[Sub Pop]].<ref name="Erlewine">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-whigs-mn0000602859|title=The Afghan Whigs - Music Biography, Credits and Discography|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> With their second album ''[[Up in It]]'' (1990) released on the label, the band toured regularly in the United States for two years and occasionally in Europe before recording ''Congregation''.<ref name="Erlewine"/> Sub Pop gave the band a $15,000 advance to record the album, which Dulli later said was a "then-unheard-of" and "bloated" amount.<ref name="Yarm">Yarm (2011), p. 307.</ref> 

The album's cover shows a nude black woman sitting on a blanket with a white baby held in her arms.<ref name="Cil<U+00EC>a">Cil<U+00EC>a (1999), p. 23.</ref> It serves as a comical reference to the band's [[African-American music]] roots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/1103951/the-40-coolest-nsfw-album-covers/franchises/listomania/attachment/afghan_whigs-congregation/|title=The 40 Coolest NSFW Album Covers The Afghan Whigs - Congregation|date=July 26, 2012|publisher=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> Along with a collective interest in [[classic rock]], band members had other individual tastes in music, including McCollum's interest in [[free jazz]], [[Experimental music|experimental]], and [[Music of India|Indian music]], and Dulli's love of [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[soul music|soul]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Spaceman|first=Brett|year=2008|url=http://www.sicmagazine.net/articles/305/interview-afghan-whigs|title=Interview - Afghan Whigs|publisher=[sic] Magazine|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> and [[funk]], particularly [[Motown]] artists and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].<ref name="CM"/>

== Recording ==
[[File:Twilight Singers Leicester.jpg|right|thumb|270px|Frontman [[Greg Dulli]] wrote most of the album.<ref name="credits"/>]]

The Afghan Whigs began recording the album in July 1991.<ref name="credits"/> They held recording sessions for ''Congregation'' at Bear Creek Studios in Woodinville, Washington and Buzz's Kitchen in Los Angeles, California.<ref name="credits"/> Dulli wrote most of its songs and produced the album with [[audio engineering|audio engineer]] Ross Ian Stein.<ref name="credits"/> Session musicians such as Miss Ruby Belle, Shecky Stein, and Lance Ellison also contributed; Belle sung lead vocals on "Her Against Me", Stein played piano on "Conjure Me", and Ellison played piano and sung lead vocals on "The Temple" with John Curley and Rick McCollum.<ref name="credits"/> Singer-songwriter [[Shawn Smith]] contributed backing vocals to "This Is My Confession" and "Dedicate It".<ref name="credits"/> After the rest of the band finished recording their parts, Dulli stayed in Los Angeles to record his vocals, [[overdubbing|overdub]] the recorded tracks, and [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] the album.<ref name="Yarm"/> However, the album's production was delayed due to Sub Pop's financial difficulties, and Dulli got another job in Los Angeles to pay for the studio.<ref name="Yarm"/> 

Although the label eventually settled the studio's bills and the album's sessions ended in August 1991,<ref name="credits"/> the band was unsure if Sub Pop had enough money to release any more albums, let alone ''Congregation''.<ref name="Yarm"/> After the massive commercial success of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s 1991 album ''[[Nevermind]]'',<ref name="Yarm"/> Sub Pop recovered financially by receiving royalties from the album after the band left them for a major label.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kurutz|first=Steve|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/jonathan-poneman-mn0001749380|title=Jonathan Poneman - Music Biography, Credits and Discography|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> Dulli later said that while he was "stranded in L.A. ... Nirvana saved the whole fuckin' label".<ref name="Yarm"/> He recalled thanking the band's frontman [[Kurt Cobain]] upon the album's completion, saying that "I went to Nirvana's show at [[Palace Theater (Los Angeles)|the Palace]] in L.A. and hugged Kurt and said, 'Good one, bro. Congratulations. And thank you<U+2014>now I can go home.'"<ref name="Yarm"/> 

After the album's sessions were done, Dulli was inspired to write and record an additional track on the day of [[Miles Davis]]' death,<ref name="Varias">{{cite journal|last=Varias|first=Chris|month=November|year=2010|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20101121112021/http://cincinnatimagazine.com/article.aspx?id=97819|title=The 50 Greatest Pop Songs Recorded in Cincinnati|journal=[[Cincinnati Magazine]]|location=Cincinnati|publisher=CM Media|accessdate=2012-08-12|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69rba8rq7|archivedate=2012-08-12}}</ref> September 28, 1991.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=September 29, 1991|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/29/nyregion/miles-davis-trumpeter-dies-jazz-genius-65-defined-cool.html|title=Miles Davis, Trumpeter, Dies; Jazz Genius, 65, Defined Cool|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=New York|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> He received two messages on his answering machine from music executive David Katznelson, the first providing directions to a cookout and the second informing Dulli that Davis had passed, saying that "Miles is dead. Don't forget the alcohol."<ref name="Varias"/> Working at Ultrasuede in Cincinnati,<ref name="credits">{{cite album-notes|title=Congregation|artist=[[The Afghan Whigs]]|publisher=[[Sub Pop]]|location=Seattle|publisherid=SPCD 130|year=1992|type=CD liner}}</ref> Dulli incorporated Katznelson's line as a lyric and, with a guitar riff from Rick McCollum, hastily recorded "Miles Iz Ded", which was included as a [[hidden track]] on the album.<ref name="Varias"/> ''Congregation'' was [[audio mastering|mastered]] by Jack Skinner at K Disc Mastering in Hollywood.<ref name="credits"/> Dulli subsequently took a drive in his car and listened to the album while observing his scenery, a practice he continued with future albums.<ref>{{cite web|date=February 19, 2011|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/0219/dullig.html|title=Greg Dulli Interview|publisher=[[RT<U+00C9>.ie|RT<U+00C9> Ten]]|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>

== Composition ==
=== Music and style ===
{{Listen|pos = left
 |filename    = Miles Iz Ded sample.ogg  
 |title       = "Miles Iz Ded"
 |description = A favorite among fans of the band,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hart|first=Josh|date=May 25, 2012|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/review-afghan-whigs-new-york-citys-bowery-ballroom|title=Review: The Afghan Whigs at New York City's Bowery Ballroom|journal=[[Guitar World]]|publisher=[[NewBay Media]]|location=New York|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> the song incorporates [[punk rock]] and [[soul music|soul]] influences and features a pseudo-[[funk]] riff.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kandell|first=Steve|date=May 24, 2012|url=http://www.spin.com/#articles/afghan-whigs-play-first-show-13-years-full-report|title=The Afghan Whigs Play First Show in 13 Years: The Full Report|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=Spin Media|location=New York|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref><ref name="RSguide"/>
}}
The album expands on aggressive sound of the band's previous work with refined musical details and occasionally slower songs.<ref name="Muze"/><ref name="Ankeny">{{cite web|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/congregation-mw0000275902|title=Congregation - The Afghan Whigs|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> In ''[[Rough Guides|The Rough Guide to Rock]]'' (2003), music journalist Alex Ogg writes that The Afghan Whigs were "managing to balance volume with subtlety" amid the burgeoning [[grunge]] music scene.<ref name="RG">Ogg et al. Buckley (2003), p. 12.</ref> The album's music incorporates heavy [[counterpoint]] rhythms, [[indie rock]] harmonics,<ref name="Weisbard">Weisbard & Marks (1995), pp. 4<U+2013>5.</ref> [[wah-wah pedal|wah-wah]] and [[slide guitar]]s,<ref name="Option"/> and [[staccato]] [[guitar riff|riffs]] with funk, [[heavy metal music|metal]], and [[blues]] influences.<ref name="Weisbard"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Butler|first=Nick|date=January 26, 2005|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/1359/The-Afghan-Whigs-Black-Love/|title=The Afghan Whigs - Black Love (staff review)|publisher=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' writer Brad Webber compares its melodies to those of "later [[H<U+00FC>sker D<U+00FC>]]".<ref name="Webber"/> ''[[Option (music magazine)|Option]]'' perceives influences from "ex-indie guitar bands" such as [[Dinosaur Jr.]] and Nirvana in the songs' "catch-iness and in the arrangements' juxtaposition of frenzy and laziness."<ref name="Option"/> David Sprague of the ''[[Trouser Press]]'' comments that the band's instrumentation "contriv[es] panoramic images through judicious use of wah-wah guitar ... and the tribal drumbeats with which Steven Earle invokes an air of ritualistic surrender."<ref name="Sprague">{{cite web|last1=Sprague|first1=David|last2=Brown|first2=Jeff|url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=afghan_whigs|title=Afghan Whigs|work=[[Trouser Press]]|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref>

The album's rock sound is complemented by a predominant soul influence.<ref name="Cil<U+00EC>a2">Cil<U+00EC>a & Guglielmi (2010), p. 42.</ref> [[Piero Scaruffi]] calls the album "a calmer and catchier collection" than ''Up in It'' and notes elements of [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and soul ballads.<ref>{{cite web|last=Scaruffi|first=Piero|authorlink=Piero Scaruffi|url=http://www.scaruffi.com/vol5/afghanwi.html|title=Afghan Whigs|publisher=Piero Scaruffi|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> Christophe Basterra of ''[[Magic (music magazine)|Magic]]'' characterizes the music as "[[Four Tops|The Four Tops]] appropriating '[[Search and Destroy (The Stooges song)|Search and Destroy]]' by [[The Stooges|Iggy & the Stooges]]".<ref name="Basterra"/> The slow-burning ballad "Let Me Lie to You" incorporates soul and grunge musical styles.<ref name="Cil<U+00EC>a"/><ref name="Phillips">{{cite web|last=Phillips|first=Amy|coauthor=et al.|date=July 11, 2008|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7150-sub-pop-20/|title=Staff Lists: Sub Pop 20|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> Dulli wrote the song in an attempt to deviate from the aesthetic of Sub Pop, whom he felt discouraged its acts from recording slow songs.<ref name="Fernandez">{{cite journal|last=Fernandez|first=J.L.|date=November 22, 2010|url=http://www.efeeme.com/greg-dulli-buscando-la-calma/|title=Greg Dulli: Buscando la calma|journal=[[:es:Efe Eme|Efe Eme]]|publisher=Filmac|language=Spanish|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> He cites writing the song as the moment he began having faith in himself as a songwriter.<ref name="Fernandez"/> Songs such as "Miles Iz Ded",<ref name="RSguide">Joe Gross et al. Brackett & Hoard (2004), pp. 9<U+2013>10.</ref> "Conjure Me", and "Turn On the Water" incorporate funk influences and wah-wah guitar.<ref name="Ankeny"/><ref name="Webber"/> [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Stephen M. Deusner cites the latter song as an example of how the band "integrate[d] African-American sounds and influences into their white [[rock music|rock]]", writing that it "uses [[Isaac Hayes]]' wakka-chikka guitars as a [[punk rock|punk]] accessory, and its jumpy guitar riffs instill these songs with a sense of motion that suggests amped-up r&b."<ref name="Deusner">{{cite web|last=Deusner|first=Stephen M.|date=May 30, 2007|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10270-unbreakable-a-retrospective/|title=The Afghan Whigs: Unbreakable (A Retrospective)|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> "Tonight" features bluesy acoustic guitar.<ref name="Lariviere"/>

=== Lyrical themes ===
{{Listen|pos = right
 |filename    = Kiss the Floor sample.ogg  
 |title       = "Kiss the Floor"
 |description = The spaciously arranged song has wistful singing by Dulli and lyrics about an empty sexual experience with a virgin.<ref name="Lariviere"/>
}}
The songs discuss dysfunctional [[intimate relationship]]s and [[sexual deviancy]],<ref name="Weisbard"/><ref name="Option"/> and feature themes of pleasure and guilt.<ref name="RSguide"/> They are narrated from the perspective of a broken sinner and [[wikt:lothario|lothario]] with sinister and narcissistic tones.<ref name="Muze">{{cite web|url=http://www.insound.com/Congregation-MP3-Afghan-Whigs/P/INS43855/|title=Congregation - MP3 - Afghan Whigs|publisher=[[Insound]]. [[Muze]]|accessdate=2012-08-16|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69yOf6TFz|archivedate=2012-08-16}}</ref><ref name="Ankeny"/> Dulli's lyrics incorporate haunting [[refrain]]s and express angst and melodrama.<ref name="Basterra">{{cite journal|last=Basterra|first=Christophe|month=June|year=2010|issue=143|url=http://www.magicrpm.com/artistes/the-afghan-whigs/a-lire/interviews/album-oublie|title=The Afghan Whigs en interview - Album oubli<U+00E9>|journal=[[Magic (music magazine)|Magic]]|publisher=Bonne Nouvelles Editions|location=Paris|language=French|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref><ref name="Webber">{{cite news|last=Webber|first=Brad|date=March 19, 1992|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-03-19/features/9201250629_1_afghan-whigs-star-husker-du|title=Afghan Whigs Congregation (Sub Pop)|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|location=Chicago|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref name="Cohen">{{cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Jason|month=May|year=1994|url=http://www.summerskiss.com/154/whigging-out/|title=Whigging Out|journal=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> His [[baritone]] vocals are moaningly husky and feature [[falsetto]] wails.<ref name="Option"/><ref name="Cohen"/> Daniel Fidler of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' compares Dulli's vocals on the album to those of "a young [[Paul Westerberg]] [[wikt:in heat|in heat]]."<ref name="Spin">{{cite journal|last1=Fidler|first1=Daniel|last2=Leopardi|first2=Nancy|month=February|year=1992|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yLVeu01ciK8C&pg=PT73#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=New Revolutions|journal=Spin|publisher=Camouflage Associates|volume=7|issue=11|accessdate=2012-08-06|location=New York|page=72}}</ref> David Sprague of the ''[[Trouser Press]]'' calls ''Congregation'' a "strangely flamboyant" album that showcases "Dulli's metamorphosis from everypunk wallflower to rakish scoundrel with a [[wikt:heart of glass|heart of glass]]."<ref name="Sprague"/> Jason Ankeny of [[Allmusic]] calls Dulli "a truly magnetic presence" and writes of his performance on the album, "by turns predator ('Tonight') and prey ('I'm Her Slave'), he's the guy your parents always warned you about, delivering each syllable of his remarkable lyrics with equal measures of innuendo and venom."<ref name="Ankeny"/> Stephanie Benson of [[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]] comments that his lyrics are "full of stifling dissatisfaction and boozy philosophy".<ref name="Benson">{{cite web|last=Benson|first=Stephanie|date=August 7, 2011|url=http://blog.rhapsody.com/2011/08/aotd0807.html|title=Afghan Whigs, Congregation|publisher=[[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]]|accessdate=2012-08-05|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69hr7NF6A|archivedate=2012-08-06}}</ref> 

"I'm Her Slave" is a [[heroin]] anecdote with lyrics narrated by a subjugate lover.<ref name="Sprague"/> Music critic [[Greg Kot]] cites "Turn On the Water" as an example of when "the twisted narrator is the victim" and "cast adrift" in Dulli's lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-12-06/news/9312060146_1_afghan-whigs-singer-greg-dulli-pearl-jam|title=Afghan Whigs' Singer Gets Dark And Dickensian In Metro Concert|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|publisher=Tribune Company|location=Chicago|date=December 6, 1993|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> Inspired by a paranoid breakup,<ref name="Lariviere"/> "Conjure Me" is told from the perspective of an aggressive predator and obscure object of desire.<ref name="Muze"/><ref name="Sprague"/> On "Kiss the Floor", the narrator recounts stealing a girl's virginity and avoiding her brothers.<ref name="Lariviere">{{cite web|last=Lariviere|first=Aaron|date=June 21, 2012|url=http://stereogum.com/1069802/the-afghan-whigs-13-most-vicious-songs/franchises/listomania/|title=The Afghan Whigs<U+2019> 13 Most Vicious Songs|publisher=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> "This Is My Confession" has a theme of [[absolution]].<ref name="RSguide"/> The lyrics depicts it as an empty sexual experience: "Shove my head against the door, crawl inside and kiss the floor / Waiting for the sun again, drink it, smoke it, stick it in."<ref name="Lariviere"/> "The Temple" is a cover of the song of the same name from the 1970 rock opera ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]''.<ref name="Muze"/> Dulli became a fan of the rock opera as a child when his babysitter played it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnston|first=Maura|authorlink=Maura Johnston|date=May 23, 2012|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2012/05/greg_dulli_interview.php?page=3|title=Q&A: The Afghan Whigs' Greg Dulli On Getting The Band Back Together, The Art Of Comedy, And Bad At-Bat Music|work=[[The Village Voice]]|publisher=[[Village Voice Media]]|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> "Let Me Lie to You" has lyrics expressing passive cruelty and subtle manipulation.<ref name="Lariviere"/> "Tonight" depicts a peaceful night as the backdrop for the narrator's corrupt one-track mind: "Follow me down to the bushes, dear / No one will know, we'll disappear / I'll hold your hand, we'll never tell / Our private little trip to hell".<ref name="Lariviere"/> The album's hidden track "Miles Iz Ded" is about seduction and alcohol,<ref name="RSguide"/> with a [[last call (bar term)|last call]] sensibility and despairing tone.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 6, 2008|url=http://idolator.com/397932/is-the-afghan-whigs-miles-iz-ded-one-of-the-greatest-songs-ever|title=Is The Afghan Whigs<U+2019> <U+201C>Miles Iz Ded<U+201D> One Of The Greatest Songs Ever?|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]]|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=January 30, 2007|url=http://idolator.com/232579/on-the-flippity-flop-the-afghan-whigs-have-a-rough-night-out|title=On The Flippity-Flop: The Afghan Whigs Have A Rough Night Out|publisher=Idolator. Buzz Media|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>

== Releasen and promotion ==
The album was released by Sub Pop on January 31, 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=1120373&style=music&fulldesc=T|title=Afghan Whigs - Congregation CD Album|publisher=[[CD Universe]]. Muze|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> and distributed by [[Caroline Records]].<ref name="credits"/> It was issed on [[LP record|LP]] and [[compact disc|CD]] formats.<ref name="Strong"/> ''Congregation'' was promoted with two [[single (music)|singles]]. "Turn On the Water" was released in January as a [[gramophone record|7-inch single]] with "Miles Iz Ded" on its [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref name="Strong"/> It was also released as a [[CD single]] coupled with the tracks "Chalk Outline" and "Miles Iz Ded".<ref name="Strong"/> On February 25, "Turn On the Water" was released as a [[cassette single]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/turn-on-the-water-mr0000275774|title=Turn on the Water - The Afghan Whigs : Release Information, Reviews and Credits|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> "Conjure Me" was released in May as a 7-inch single backed with a cover of [[The Supremes]]' 1965 song "[[My World Is Empty Without You]]".<ref name="Strong"/> A music video for the single was filmed, featuring a topless woman caressing Dulli as he lip syncs the song,<ref>{{cite web|last=Solomon|first=Dan|date=December 8, 2011|url=http://www.mtvhive.com/2011/12/08/hive-five-afghan-whigs-reuniting/|title=Hive Five: Advice for the Reformed Afghan Whigs|publisher=[[MTV Music|MTV Hive]]. [[MTV]]|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> and received rotation on [[MTV]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=qRAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Clip List|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=BPI Communications|page=45|accessdate=2012-08-12|date=June 20, 1992|volume=140|issue=25}}</ref> ''Congregation'' was [[reissue]]d in September 1998.<ref name="Strong">Strong (2004), p. 20.</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on November 22, 1999, through [[PIAS Recordings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hmv.com/hmvweb/displayProductDetails.do?ctx=280;-1;-1;-1;-1&sku=327978|title=Afghan Whigs: Congregation (1999): CD|publisher=[[HMV Group|HMV]]|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>

The Afghan Whigs promoted the album with an appearance on MTV and an international tour with dates in major American cities and Europe.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Winternitz|first=Felix|month=April|year=1992|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tOsCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Observer's Notebook|journal=Cincinnati Magazine|location=Cincinnati|publisher=CM Media|page=14|volume=25|issue=17|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> During their shows, the band interspersed R&B songs in their set list, including an [[interpolation (music)|interpolation]] of [[The Spinners (American R&B group)|The Spinners]]' 1972 song "[[I'll Be Around (The Spinners song)|I'll Be Around]]" in "Turn On the Water".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Afghan Whigs|journal=[[Musician (magazine)|Musician]]|publisher=Amordian Press|year=1994|page=168|issue=183<U+2013>188}}</ref> Their extensive touring for the album gained the band a larger audience.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bambarger|first=Bradley|date=February 3, 1996|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_w4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Afghan Whigs Get Passionate|journal=Billboard|publisher=BPI Communications|volume=108|issue=5|page=35|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref>

