| rev9Score = 4/5<!-- staff rating acceptable, per Wikipedia:ALBUMS/REVSITE --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/soundoff.php?albumid=7995|title=The Afghan Whigs - Congregation User Opinions|publisher=Sputnikmusic|accessdate=2012-08-05|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69hnN4cGb|archivedate=2012-08-05|at=''Scroll down to'' Nick Butler (staff)}}</ref>
| rev10 = [[Yahoo! Music]]
| rev10Score = mixed<ref name="Norris"/>
}}
Although it did not [[record chart|chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/album/afghan-whigs/congregation/1167|title=Congregation - Afghan Whigs|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref> ''Congregation'' received very positive reviews from [[music criticism|music critics]] upon its release.<ref name="Erlewine"/> Michael Azerrad of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called it "superb".<ref name="CM">Escamilla (1996), p. 5.</ref> Daniel Fidler of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' called the album "a clean move toward musical excellence" and commented that it "shows the band bursting its Sub Pop chains with catchy, heavy guitar riffs, downright lovable song arrangements, melodies that jerk your emotions back and forth, and yes, endearing, raspy vocals that wail, moan, scream, and shout".<ref name="Spin"/> Brad Webber of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' described the album as "a more accessible brand of music than normally associated with the Seattle-Minneapolis axis of grunge guitar groups."<ref name="Webber"/> He found The Afghan Whigs to be "on rock's cutting edge" and commented that the band "stirs a torrent of emotions on neatly paced songs".<ref name="Webber"/> 

[[J. D. Considine]] of ''[[Musician (magazine)|Musician]]'' characterized the band as "clever enough to find hooks in the sort of gnarled riffs and guitar noise [[Fugazi]] plays for atmosphere", as well as "canny enough to avoid most of the mannerisms that make much Amerindie rock seem so cliched."<ref name="Considine">{{cite journal|last=Considine|first=J. D.|authorlink=J. D. Considine|title=Review: Congregation|page=13|month=January|year=1992|issue=163|journal=Musician|publisher=Amordian Press}}</ref> Considine concluded in his review, "The best reason to join this ''Congregation'' is that the songs are catchy enough to hold their own against the best work of bands like Dinosaur Jr. or [[The Replacements (band)|the Replacements]]."<ref name="Considine"/> In a mixed review, ''[[Option (music magazine)|Option]]'' commended the album's "sheer listenability", "clear recording and dynamic performances", but criticized Dulli's subject matter and panned the band's cover of "The Temple".<ref name="Option">{{cite journal|title=Review: Congregation|journal=[[Option (music magazine)|Option]]|publisher=Sonic Options Network|location=Los Angeles|month=May/June|year=1992|page=89}}</ref> ''[[Melody Maker]]'' ranked the album number 25 on its year-end best albums for 1992.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The best and worst of 1992|journal=[[Melody Maker]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|location=London|date=January 2, 1993}}</ref>

With the album's critical acclaim and their steady touring,<ref>{{cite news|last=Maurstad|first=Tom|date=May 3, 1992|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D238138505F5&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Teenage Fanclub upstaged by opener, Power-generating Afghan Whigs proves to be a tough act to follow|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|publisher=[[Belo]]|location=Dallas|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> the band attained a [[cult following]] and was courted by several [[record label#major label|major labels]] who wanted to sign them.<ref name="Erlewine"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Karampeazis|first=Aris|url=http://www.mic.gr/artist.asp?id=2202|title=<U+039A><U+03B1><U+03BB><U+03BB><U+03B9><U+03C4><U+03AD><U+03C7><U+03BD><U+03B7><U+03C2> - The Afghan Whigs - Alternative|publisher=MIC|language=Greek|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> Frustrated with the distribution limitation of a small record label,<ref name="CM"/> they signed to [[Elektra Records]] after their final release for Sub Pop, an EP of soul cover songs called ''[[Uptown Avondale]]'' (1992).<ref name="Erlewine"/> Their major label debut ''[[Gentlemen (album)|Gentlemen]]'' was released in 1993 to critical acclaim and mainstream exposure.<ref name="Erlewine"/>

== Legacy ==
{{Quote box
 |quote = The first band hailing from outside the Pacific Northwest to join the [[Sub Pop]] stable, Ohio's Afghan Whigs brought a healthy injection of libido to the label's angsty roster ... [L]eering frontman [[Greg Dulli]] used ''Congregation'' to cultivate the stylized, seductive evil that he would go on to perfect on the Whigs' 1993 masterwork ''[[Gentlemen (album)|Gentlemen]]''. 
 |source = <U+2014> Amy Phillips, [[Pitchfork Media]]<ref name="Phillips"/>
 |align = right
 |salign = center
 |width = 31%
 |border = 1px
 |fontsize = 90%
}}
Along with ''Gentlemen'', ''Congregation'' is generally considered by music writers to be part of The Afghan Whigs' peak era.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sprague|first=Deborah|date=May 23, 2012|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117947634|title=Afghan Whigs|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Deming|first=Mark|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-in-it-mw0000677565|title=Up in It - The Afghan Whigs|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Scanlon|first=James|date=August 8, 2012|url=http://www.praguepost.com/night-and-day/stage/13932-preview-the-afghan-whigs.html|title=Preview: The Afghan Whigs|newspaper=[[The Prague Post]]|publisher=Prague Post, spol. s.r.o.|location=Prague|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> Dulli cites it as "the record where we came into our own".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bains|first=Lee|month=May|year=2007|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JSsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Dulli Noted|journal=[[CMJ|CMJ New Music Monthly]]|publisher=CMJ Network|location=New York|page=10|issue=147|accessdate=2012-08-06}}</ref> ''Melody Maker'' dubbed it "the finest rock LP of the decade" and commented that it is "nothing less than rock raping pop, a ferocious deflowering of [[Motown]]'s romantic ideal".<ref name="MM">{{cite journal|title=Review: Congregation|journal=Melody Maker|publisher=IPC Media|location=London|date=July 13, 1996|page=51}}</ref> With ''Congregation'', Stephanie Benson of [[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]] found the band to be "crucial to the birth of '90s alternative rock."<ref name="Benson"/> [[Allmusic]] editor Jason Ankeny viewed the album as the band's artistic breakthrough and "ticket to the big leagues", calling it "an incendiary and insidious set which bridges the gap between the noisy aggression of the band's early releases and the soulful swagger of their later work."<ref name="Ankeny"/> Ankeny also cited it as "the grunge era's most overlooked masterpiece" and an indication of the band's musical growth, writing that "while still unmistakably a member of the Sub Pop stable, there's a greater maturity and depth to their sinewy sound, with a newfound grasp of mood and nuance".<ref name="Ankeny"/> 

[[Yahoo! Music]]'s Chris Norris called it a "disjointed set, which finds the band suspended between its punky roots and a more voluptuous later style."<ref name="Norris">{{cite web|last=Norris|first=Chris|url=http://music.ca.launch.yahoo.com/read/review/12032513|title=The Afghan Whigs Review|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]. [[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=2012-08-06|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69hsmaY7n|archivedate=2012-08-06}}</ref> The ''Spin Alternative Record Guide'' (1995) noted "a creative musical blend" on the album, but concluded that "the results feel like dress rehearsals for ''Gentlemen'', with one partial exception, 'Conjure Me,' and one absolute triumph: a surging final track ... that might be the Afghan Whigs' strongest recorded performance."<ref name="Weisbard"/> In ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (2004), ''Rolling Stone'' journalist Joe Gross gave the album three-and-a-half out of five stars and viewed it as a "quantum leap" over the band's previous work, commenting that it "shows that they ditched grunge for soul because they were no damn good at the former and ladies dig the latter."<ref name="RSguide"/> In 2002, Italian music magazine ''[[:it:Il Mucchio Selvaggio (rivista)|Il Mucchio Selvaggio]]'' included the album in its list of 100 Best Albums by Decade.<ref>{{cite journal|title=100 Best Albums by Decade|journal=[[:it:Il Mucchio Selvaggio (rivista)|Il Mucchio Selvaggio]]|location=Roma|language=Italian|publisher=Stemax S.r.l.|year=2002}}</ref> Polish webzine [[:pl:Screenagers|Screenagers]] ranked it number 79 on its 2004 list of the Top 100 Albums of the '90s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenagers.pl/index.php?service=xtras&action=show&id=13|title=Najlepsze p<U+0142>yty lat 90-tych|publisher=[[:pl:Screenagers|Screenagers]]|language=Polish|date=March 22, 2004|accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> Italian music journalist [[:it:Eddy Cil<U+00EC>a|Eddy Cil<U+00EC>a]] and [[:it:Federico Guglielmi|Federico Guglielmi]] included ''Congregation'' in their 2010 book on essential rock albums.<ref name="Cil<U+00EC>a2"/>

